    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> To Quote Han Solo, &quot;She may not look like much but she&#39;s got it where it counts.&quot;<br>
<br>
It&#39;s not pretty, and it&#39;s got weaknesses, but this deck goes through cards fast.  The hobbit side usually plays 2-3 events per round.  Deploys swords, armors and tales (most of them for 1 or for zero twilight)<br>
<br>
The shadow side has enough trackers that roaming penalty is few, so card throughput is strong.  It is not uncommon to draw all 70 cards over the course of the game.<br>
<br>
Okay, you want to go second, but if you go first, no problem, use the pony and pull Aragorn.  <br>
<br>
Fellowship strat:<br>
<br>
Pre site 6, stealth your way through any encounter, let Aragorn and Mery bash on the bad guys.  Every hobbit has the Aragorn signet, so make sure to take advantage of that.<br>
<br>
Set up for the bridge and make sure you have the <br>
stealth cards needed to avoid the Balrog.<br>
<br>
After the bridge the Hobbits get mad.  You should have them all (except pippin) armed, and still have some dagger strikes, and stealth cards ready to go for damage adders.  And you should have there and back again ready.  So now all of a sudden Frodo is between 8 and 15 power, Sam is 7-14 power as is Mery.  These hobbits can win fights once they are out of Moria.<br>
<br>
Aragorn has 2 athelas primarily to remove Nazgul conditions.  As the hobbits won&#39;t take much damage, you won&#39;t be pressed for healing.<br>
<br>
Against Nazgul:  Stealth to avoid battles (Duh).  Use Aragorn and his sword + dagger strike to kill them when you can.<br>
<br>
Against Moria:  Paths, and your hobbits (there and back again) should be able to take most moria encounters.<br>
<br>
Sauron:  We have a hard time there when too many UTWEs get out.  Start by having Pippin take the hits, then Mery, then Aragorn.  The Orc Bowmen are somewhat reduced as the Mithril coat takes a little bite out of them.  Basically, you have to move fast against Sauron before they can get too many of those conditions out.<br>
<br>
Isengard:  Much like the nazgul, stealth away.  Watch out for wariness.  Use sting to check his hand. If you spot a wariness, then use &#39;there and back again&#39; and dagger strikes to beat off the Uruk&#39;s.<br>
<br>
Shadow strat:<br>
Early Bowmen and UTWE&#39;s are the key.<br>
<br>
The Scimitar and Forces of Mordor can set up a nasty hit especially when added to Band of the Eye or the big bad Morgual man.  If you draw a Forces of Mordor early, watch for a chance to clobber the ring bearer early with scouts.<br>
<br>
You have a good amount of exert to wound minions, so between UTWE, Bowmen and exert to wound, you should have the fellow ship injured and dying most of the time. <br>
<br>
Glandalf and sleep or intimidate cause this deck some problems, so killing him should be a priority (albeit it takes a mistake on your opponents part to make him vulnerable.)<br>
<br>
Now to address some No this&#39; and No thats&#8217;<br>
<br>
No Elbreth - It&#39;s a meta thing.  If you think it&#39;s nazgul, add the elbreths and drop the PATHs.<br>
<br>
No bilbo? - Yeah we can endure those conditions.  Athelas will get them off your people, and Aragorn and his trusty heal every round will fight off the &#39;You move you wound&#39; damage.  Pippin who is a meat shield will be taking those wounds most of the time.<br>
<br>
<br>
No tower assassin? - Couldn&#39;t find space.  I need all those trackers, (to fight roaming cost and to get out UTWE&#39;s. and I need those exert to wound minions to compliment the UTWE&#8217;s.  I suppose I could replace the inquisitors with some assassins, but I like throwing cards out of my opponents hand.<br>
<br>
No corruption?  I have found wound/overwhelm to be more successful in my area.  Just preference.<br>
<br>
Thanks for reading and I hope you enjoy it.<br>
<br>
